Although endophytes have been studied for a long time, they were found to be able to mimic the secondary metabolite repertoire of host plants only in the last two decades (
 Venugopalan and Srivastava, 2015). Endophytes can produce biologically active compounds, which are very important for increasing the adaptability of endophytes and their host plants, including tolerance to biotic and abiotic stresses (
 Rai et al., 2014; 
 Golinska et al., 2015). More importantly, many compounds with unique structures and highly biologically active secondary metabolites were isolated from endophytes. An increasing number of novel compounds are being isolated from endophytic fungi and actinomycetes, including alkaloids, peptides, steroids, terpenoids, quinones, flavonoids, aliphatic compounds, and phenols (
 Strobel and Daisy, 2003; 
 Golinska et al., 2015; 
 Deshmukh et al., 2018). These compounds have been proved to have the biological activities previously shown, including antimicrobial, antiviral, larvicidal, antimalarial, anti-tumor and antidiabetic (
 Strobel and Daisy, 2003; 
 Golinska et al., 2015; 
 Matsumoto and Takahashi, 2017). Therefore, isolation of endophytes from medicinal plants may provide new opportunities to discover diverse species and natural products using for medicine, agriculture, and industry (
 Aly et al., 2011; 
 Ding et al., 2013; 
 Golinska et al., 2015; 
 Jeewon et al., 2019; 
 Bibi et al., 2020).
